article.description:
Howard Eisley hit two 3-pointers as part of an
8-0 run to end the third quarter, putting the New York Knicks in
control for good in a 100-90 victory over the Toronto Raptors on
Monday night.
article.headline: Eisley sparks key third-quarter run for Knicks
article.linkText: Frustrated Raptors fall short against Eisley, Knicks
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Knicks have caught the Washington Wizards in the win column, and they still believe they can catch the Milwaukee Bucks in the standings.
Eisley

Howard Eisley hit two 3-pointers as part of an 8-0 run to end the third quarter, putting the Knicks in control for good in a 100-90 victory over the Toronto Raptors on Monday night. New York, in 10th place in the conference, moved within 2½ games of the Bucks while matching ninth-place Washington's total of 32 victories. The Knicks still have two more losses than the Wizards, who are currently on a six-game Western road trip that began with two defeats. If the Knicks can move past Washington, there will be only one more team standing between them and the postseason. "That's what we're thinking, but honestly it's one game at a time,'' Latrell Sprewell said. "You can't look too far ahead, but we are definitely watching the standings and seeing where other teams are. That's why a game like tonight's is very important to win.'' Entering a crucial five-game stretch in which they will play the Raptors and Nets twice apiece before traveling to Denver to face the Nuggets, the Knicks probably need to win at least four times to stay in the playoff hunt. Because they lost the season series with Milwaukee, they must finish a game ahead of the Bucks to claim the eighth spot in the East. It would be quite an accomplishment for a team that began the season with eight losses in the first nine games. "We don't really look at the past anymore at this point. It's even dangerous to look back at this game,'' Allan Houston said. "We need to concentrate on what got us over the hump tonight, which is intensity.'' The Knicks went ahead by as many as 16 in the fourth quarter in sending Toronto to its ninth loss in 10 games. Kurt Thomas scored 23 and Houston added 20 for the Knicks, while Eisley and Sprewell scored 13 apiece. Antonio Davis scored 23 and Vince Carter had 21 for the Raptors, although Carter was held to just five points in the second half. "It's not a lack of effort. I'm not going to say that, but a lack of concentration coming into the second half,'' Carter said. The Knicks made five of their eight 3-pointers in the second half, and Eisley's pair in a 69-second span of the third quarter took the Raptors out of the game. The first gave New York a 66-64 lead and was followed by a 22-footer by Sprewell. Eisley's next 3 made it a seven-point game, and Toronto coach Lenny Wilkens shook his head in disgust when Morris Peterson threw the ball away on a baseball pass with 14 seconds remaining in the quarter and the Raptors needing to hold for one shot. Carter came back to the bench and kicked a chair with 5:52 left in the fourth after Clarence Weatherspoon hit a corner jumper to give New York an 87-74 lead. The Raptors made one final run, pulling to 96-86 with 2:15 left after consecutive 3-pointers by Peterson and Alvin Williams. A bank shot by Davis made it an eight-point game, but Peterson missed a jumper with 56 seconds left that would have cut it to six. Game notes
Sprewell was alarmed when courtside patron Calvin Klein, the fashion designer, walked up to speak to him as he was about to throw an inbounds pass late in the fourth quarter. "No, I wasn't nervous. I was a little surprised, like is security going to come over here at some point or what? I didn't know that was him,'' Sprewell said. ... Davis left the game with 16.8 seconds remaining holding his right hand. The diagnosis was a jammed finger. ... Michael Bradley started at power forward for Toronto for the second straight game. After shooting 5-for-5 against Philadelphia, he was 5-for-5 against the Knicks until firing up a badly off-target jumper with 5 seconds remaining. ... The Knicks have beaten Toronto seven consecutive times. ... Toronto dropped to 0-14 on the second night of back-to-back games. ... The Raptors have failed to reach 100 points in their last 24 games against the Knicks.
